ron-gnats eat any lazy tool. Third, I say the dates and the tides aloud so our memories cannot lie to us later, and I invite any Brinewarden in this hall to swear whether the crate I saw was bound for a patrol cutter or a private skiff. I do not accuse a cartel by name because the water will carry any name I shout further than my proof; instead I accuse the pattern, and I accuse the timing, and I ask the Council to see those two things as clearly as I do. The tolls can wait a fortnight for an honest inquiry, because hunger is a slow killer and bad law is a fast one, and I will not hand a blade to anyone who pretends their purse is a shield.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Mother Tullis Nacrethane\", \"lines\": \"Children of the First Shell bow to no ledger that forgets a mouth, and I bring you five rows of mouths that have learned to chew quietly so rich bellies are not disturbed. You know their names because when you sleep badly you hear them, the way the mangroves whisper on fog nights, reminding you that the sea keeps all its receipts whether the Council writes them down or not. Toll their bread and you toll their bones, because the price of a pearl on Pearl Row always ends up being a shoe or a blanket or a medicine bottle in the low wards. Those who argue for urgency have built the emergency themselves and now offer to rent you a ladder to climb out, and I ask you whether you plan to thank them when the rungs keep breaking under anyone who is not rich. Delay is not cowardice when it saves lives; it is a sacred shape of courage, the kind that holds still while a wave passes so the boat does not capsize.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Ysger Thorn\", \"lines\": \"I do not love speeches, but I love a harbor that does not burn and a ledger that does not lie, and I am tired of chasing shadows that turn into contracts when I get close. I have cutters laid up for lack of honest fittings, and if a comptroller is skimming, I want his teeth on my desk and his stamp broken under